==Background==
  +
Eliza Doolittle was born in [[City of Westminster|Westminster]], London in 1988. She comes from a family with a successful and varied musical background, Her father is [[John Caird (director)|John Caird]],<ref name="Savage">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10600745|title=Talking Shop: Eliza Doolittle|last=Savage|first=Mark|date=13-07-2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2010}}</ref> an English stage director and writer of plays, musicals and operas who is also an Honorary Associate Director of the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]]. Her mother is English musical theatre actress and recording artist [[Frances Ruffelle]],<ref name="Savage"/> who won a [[Tony Award]] for her role of [[Ãponine]] in the English language version of [[Les MisÃ©rables]]. Doolittle is the granddaughter of [[Sylvia Young]],<ref name="Savage"/> who founded her theatre school in 1981.
  +   +
She has eight siblings. Her parents split when she was four years old.<ref>The Chris Moyles Show 8 December 2010 at 6:30AM http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wbqzs</ref>
  +   +
Doolittle grew up in [[Camden Town]] and attended [[Channing School For Girls]] - which was the inspiration for her songs which were around rumours and gossip. She was used to being around stages and seeing her mother singing, (Ruffelle represented the UK in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] in 1994, when Doolittle was 6 years old)<ref name="VIP"/> so had always wanted to become a recording artist and write music.<ref name="interview">{{cite web|url=http://www.rivmixx.com/interview/show/17555|title=Interview: Eliza Doolittle|date=05-07-2010|accessdate=29 December 2010}}</ref> She chose the stage name of ''Eliza Doolittle'', the [[My Fair Lady]] character, because it was her nickname as a child.<ref name="VIP">{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/artist/eliza-doolittle/pack-up.html|title=VIP track: Eliza Doolittle|date=098-05-2010|accessdate=29 December 2010}}</ref>
  +   +
==Musical career==
  +
Before entering the charts, Doolittle toured the UK with her band to gain recognition. This later turned into the "Playground Unplugged" tour where she performed at secondary schools [[Hagley RC High School]], [[The Magna Carta School]], [[The Bewdley School and Sixth Form Centre]], [[Highworth Grammar School]] and [[Presdales School]].{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}
  +   +
The first release from Doolittle is a self-titled EP that features four tracks 'Rollerblades', 'Moneybox', 'Police Car' and 'Go Home'. This was released on 29 November 2009. Tracks from the EP were remixed by Plastic Little ('Rollerblades'), [[Sam Young DJ|Sam Young]] and Jamie from [[The xx]] ('Money Box'). The EP received radio plays from [[Rob Da Bank]], [[Nick Grimshaw]],<ref name="Nick Grimshaw 4/11/2009">{{citation|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/nickgrimshaw/tracklistingarchive.shtml?20091104|title=Wednesday 4th November}}</ref> [[Fearne Cotton]] and [[Jo Whiley]].
  +   +

==Modelling career==
  +
In 2010 Doolittle was made an 'ambassador' for a [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] running game and did some modelling work to promote the concept in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/101019-eliza-doolittle-talks-lily-allen.aspx|title=Our Fair Lady|last=Alexander|first=Ella|date=2010-10-19|work=Vogue|accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref> In January 2011 it was anounced that Doolittle had been been signed by London based [[Select Model Management|Select Models]], the agency that launched the career of [[Sienna Miller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/110120-eliza-doolittle-signs-with-select-m.aspx|title=Singer-Turned-Model|last=Milligan|first=Lauren|date=2011-01-20|work=Vogue|accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref><p>Doolittle told [[Metro]] that she does not believe she looks like a model, but hoped that the signing would help raise her profile.<ref>http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/853720-eliza-doolittle-moves-on-from-brits-snub-by-landing-modelling-job "Eliza Doolittle lands modelling job" metro.co.uk</ref></p>
